<b>Permanent mail ballot list</b>
<ul>
<li>Voters can sign up for the permanent mail ballot list by checking the box when returning their application 
   for an absentee ballot to their local clerk.

<li>Voters whose names are on the permanent mail ballot list will automatically receive an absentee ballot 
   from their local clerk for all upcoming elections.

<li>Voters who wish to have their name removed from the permanent mail ballot list should send a signed letter 
    to their local clerk.

<li>Voters who are on the permanent mail ballot list can still vote in person. 
   <ul>
   <li>If the voter has <b>marked</b> their absentee ballot, they can return it to their early voting site 
       or Election Day polling place. 

   <li>If the voter brings their <b>unmarked</b> absentee ballot with them to an early voting site or 
       Election Day polling place, they can turn in the ballot and be issued a new ballot to vote. 

   <li>If the voter <b>does not have their absentee ballot</b>
       with them when they show up to vote in person, the poll workers will call the local clerk’s office 
       to confirm that the voter’s absentee ballot has not been received back.&nbsp;
       Once confirmed, the voter’s absentee ballot will be canceled and the voter can vote in person instead. 
   </ul>

<li>If a voter moves within Michigan, as long as they update their address with their new city or township clerk, 
     their permanent mail ballot status will follow them.
</ul>

<b>How do I sign up to be placed on the permanent mail ballot list?</b>
<ul>
<li>Voters can sign up for the permanent mail ballot list by checking the box on an absentee ballot application 
   from their local clerk.&nbsp; Once on the list, the voter's local clerk will automatically mail an 
   absentee ballot to the voter for all future elections.
</ul>

<b>How can I get my name removed from the permanent mail ballot list?</b>
<ul>
<li>Voters should send their local clerk a signed letter asking that their name be removed from the 
    permanent mail ballot list.
<li>A voter's name may also be removed by the local clerk if:
   <ul>
   <li>the clerk receives reliable information that the voter has moved.
   <li>the voter is no longer qualified to vote in the state.
   <li>the voter does not vote in six years.
   </ul>
</ul>

<b>If my name is removed from the permanent mail ballot list, what do I need to do to have it reinstated?</b>
<ul>
<li>Voters will need to contact their local clerk in writing.&nbsp;
    The clerk will want to make sure that the voter's registration information is up 
    to date and will add their name back to the permanent mail ballot list.
</ul>

<b>What if I'm on the permanent mail ballot list and want to vote in person?</b>
<ul>
<li>Voters on the permanent mail ballot list can vote in person as long as they have 
   not already submitted their absentee ballot. 
   <ul>
   <li>If the voter has marked their absentee ballot, they can return  it to their early voting
         site or Election Day polling place. 
   <li>If the voter brings their unmarked absentee ballot with them to an early voting site or
       Election Day polling place, they can turn in the ballot and be issued a new ballot to vote. 
   <li>If the voter does not have their absentee ballot with them when they show up to vote in person,
       the poll workers will call the local clerk’s office to confirm that the voter’s absentee ballot 
       has not been received back.&nbsp; 
       Once confirmed, the voter’s absentee ballot will be canceled and the voter can vote in person instead.
    </ul>
</ul>

<b>Will I remain on the permanent mail ballot list if I move?</b>
<ul>
<li>Yes, the permanent mail ballot list follows the voter as long as they are registered in Michigan.&nbsp;
     Whenever a voter moves, they should immediately inform their local clerk in order to keep their 
     voter registration information accurate and up to date.
</ul>

<b>If I fill out the U.S. Postal Service mail forwarding post card, will my absentee ballot be forwarded to my new address?</b>
<ul>
<li>No, the U.S. Postal Service does not forward election mail.&nbsp;
    Election mail is defined as any item mailed to or from authorized election officials that enables citizens 
    to take part in the voting process -- including ballots, voter registration cards, absentee voting applications, 
    and polling place notifications. 
<li>If a permanent mail ballot list voter will be at a different address at the time of an election, 
     the voter can contact their city or township clerk in writing to provide a different address where they want 
     their ballot mailed. 
<li>Election mail should not be confused with political mail, which is any material mailed for
    campaign purposes by a registered political candidate, campaign committee, or committee of
    a political party, as well as any material mailed by a political action committee or organization engaging in 
    issue advocacy or voter mobilization.
</ul>

<b>Do I have to fill out my absentee ballot if I'm on the permanent mail ballot list?</b>
<ul>
<li>Being on the permanent mail ballot list only guarantees that the voter will receive a ballot for 
     each upcoming election.&nbsp;
      To be counted, the absentee ballot still needs to be filled out and returned to the local clerk to 
      be tabulated.&nbsp;
      Voters on the permanent mail ballot list can decide to vote in person as long as 
      they have not already submitted their absentee ballot. 
</ul>

<b>What if I receive someone else's absentee ballot at my address?</b>
<ul>
<li>If a voter receives someone else's ballot in their mailbox, they should write "Return to sender" 
    or "No longer at this address" on the envelope and put it back in the mail. 
<li>Voters who try to vote someone else's ballot are guilty of the serious crime of election fraud.&nbsp;
    Several rigorous checks and balances performed by local clerks, are in place to make sure 
    that a voter can vote the correct ballot only once and that elections are fair, accurate, and safe.
</ul>

<b>What if I'm on the permanent mail ballot list, but I still get an absentee ballot application in the mail?</b>
<ul>
<li>Political organizations and campaigns often send absent voter applications to voters before elections, 
    regardless of voter request or need. 
<li>If you have questions about your absentee ballot status, check 
    <a href="https://Michigan.gov/Vote"
           onClick="return externalLink(this);" target="_blank"
    >Michigan.gov/Vote</a> or contact your local clerk.

<li>You are not required to submit another application after you have already joined the permanent mail ballot list. 
</ul>

<b>Can I join the permanent mail ballot list and then request to not be sent a ballot for specific elections?</b>
<ul>
<li>No, the permanent mail ballot list does not allow for voters to opt out of specific elections.&nbsp;
    Clerks have the constitutional requirement to send absentee ballots to all permanent mail ballot 
    voters in every election they are eligible to vote in. 
<li>Voters who do not wish to receive absentee ballots in every election they are eligible to vote in 
    should forgo the permanent mail ballot list and instead fill out absentee ballot applications 
    before each election they would like to receive an absentee ballot.
</ul>



